# XIS Agent Notes

This repository treats Markdown documentation as the canonical knowledge source.

## Documentation Layers

- `README.md` is the public GitHub entry point for XIS users.
- `docs/user/*` is user-facing documentation. Organize it by public API behavior and workflows.
- `docs/user/advanced/*` is for optional or specialized capabilities. Do not present client-side storage as a core
  requirement; it is a convenience feature because applications can also keep state on the server.
- Module README files are mostly for framework developers and maintainers.
- `docs/framework/*` is cross-module maintainer documentation.
- `docs/agent/*` contains agent-specific rules.

## Source Material

The old documentation app lives in `docs-app` or `/Users/bernd/projects/xis-docs`. It is source material only. Do not
copy its structure blindly into Markdown.

When reconciling old and new documentation, merge them. The old documentation often has the better learning order and
contains explanatory material that must not disappear. The newer Markdown documentation may already contain corrected,
expanded, or newly tested behavior. Preserve newer correct material while restoring missing explanations and a
reader-friendly sequence from the old documentation.

## Runtime Sources For Template Documentation

When documenting XIS template behavior, verify the current runtime sources before treating old docs as authoritative:

- `xis-javascript/src/main/js/classes/init/DomNormalizer.js`: framework elements, attribute syntax, and normalization
  between tag and attribute forms.
- `xis-javascript/src/main/js/classes/init/HandlerBuilder.js`: which normalized elements and attributes receive runtime
  behavior, such as page links, frontlet links, action links, action buttons, forms, inputs, and submit controls.
- `xis-javascript/src/main/js/classes/parse/ELFunctions.js`: built-in expression-language functions.

Use the old documentation app for editorial structure and examples, but use these runtime files to confirm what actually
exists.

## Template Completion Rule

Template behavior is only really done when all three layers agree:

- runtime code supports the behavior
- integration tests cover what the Java action/model side receives or renders
- `docs/user/*` explains the public behavior with copyable examples

For template features that exist in both forms, always think in pairs:

- attribute syntax, for example `<input xis:binding="name">`
- element syntax, for example `<xis:input binding="name">`

Both forms are worth testing because `DomNormalizer.js` can break one while the other still works.

For form controls, tests should assert what reaches the `@Action` method through `@FormData`, not merely that a DOM value
changed or a request-like payload was assembled. Repeated bindings are intentional: multiple controls with the same
binding can submit multiple values into a Java collection.

## Client Storage Rule

`@LocalStorage`, `@SessionStorage`, and `@ClientStorage` are parameter annotations in the controller API. They are meant
for key-based exchange of selected browser-state values, not for sending the whole browser storage to the server.

The server derives the relevant storage keys from controller method parameters and writes those keys into the client
configuration. The client sends all configured keys for the current page/frontlet with a request, independent of whether
the currently invoked action actually uses every key. This avoids predicting controller behavior in JavaScript.

After a controller method runs, storage parameters are written back to the response so object mutations made inside the
action are stored in the browser. This is most natural for mutable DTO-like values; do not assume method return values
annotated with storage annotations are part of the public API unless the annotation target and tests confirm it.

## Security Documentation Rules

Security documentation must describe the concrete interfaces users implement, not only the concept. For local
authentication this means `UserInfoService`. For XIS as an OpenID Connect provider this means `IDPService`, including
client registration through `IDPClientInfo` and user/client linkage through `IDPUserInfo`.

Keep user documentation focused on direct user dependencies only:

- `xis-spring` for Spring applications
- `xis-boot` for standalone applications
- `xis-test` for user-facing tests
- `xis-authentication` for protected pages, local login, and external OpenID Connect login
- `xis-idp-server` for running XIS as an OpenID Connect provider

Do not tell users to add transitive implementation modules such as `xis-idp-client`, `xis-controller-api`,
`xis-validation`, or `xis-context`. Those names belong in module README files or framework documentation, not in
`docs/user/*`.

When documenting XIS as IDP, mention that user code fills application claims while XIS fills technical token fields such
as `sub`, `iss`, `iat`, `exp`, `nbf`, and `client_id` during token creation.

Security changes should stay coupled to E2E coverage in `/Users/bernd/projects/xis-end-to-end-tests`. XIS-as-IDP is
covered there by a two-process setup: one XIS app runs as an OpenID Connect provider, another XIS app consumes it through
the normal external provider flow. The multiple-provider case combines that XIS IDP with a mock OpenID Connect provider
and must verify that the provider selection page offers both links and that choosing XIS completes the protected-page
login.

## Refresh Event Rules

Refresh events are a general UI refresh feature, not an SSO feature. SSO can use the same transport internally, but user
documentation and E2E tests should explain the normal application case first, such as a cart counter, dashboard tile, or
notification badge.

Keep these cases distinct in code, docs, and tests:

- `publishToAll` targets every connected client, anonymous or authenticated.
- `publishToClient` targets one browser client. This is not the same as a user.
- `publishToUser` targets all connected clients of one authenticated user and therefore requires authentication.
- `publishToAllUsers` targets authenticated clients only.

`FrontletResponse.reloadFrontlet(...)` is not a broadcast event. It is an action-response special case for refreshing
another already visible frontlet in the current browser. Do not describe it as needed for the current page or the
frontlet that handled the action; those are updated by the normal action response. Use it for a separate frontlet that is
not otherwise refreshed, for example a header cart summary after an action in a product-list frontlet.

When changing refresh behavior, inspect both sides:

- server: `RefreshEventPublisher`, `RefreshEvent`, `RefreshTarget`, `SseService`, `MainController`, and
  `ControllerWrapper`
- browser: `SseConnector`, `PageController.handleUpdateEvents`, `FrontletContainers.handleUpdateEvents`,
  `FrontletContainerHandler.handleActionResponse`, and `FrontletResponse.reloadFrontlet` handling

## Example Discipline

Documentation examples are part of the public API.

When documenting public behavior:

- include copyable Java examples
- include matching HTML templates when relevant
- prefer examples that can become tests
- avoid pseudocode for annotation names, template attributes, and file locations

The long-term goal is that documented examples are executable or covered by the test suite.

## Collaboration Discipline

Treat user statements about desired documentation structure as strong input, not as unquestioned final architecture.
Check them against the codebase, the old documentation, and the reader's path. If the user points out a missing concept,
make sure it appears where a reader would naturally look, even if the detailed material lives on a separate page.

## Website Policy

A documentation website may be built later, including a project wizard. The website should render or import the
Markdown documentation instead of becoming a second manually maintained copy.
